# Copy to `.env` in this folder (Vite injects `VITE_*` into the client bundle).
#
# --- Deploy / Phantom ---
# Phantom (and `window.solana`) only work in a browser "secure context": https:// URLs, or
# http://localhost / http://127.0.0.1. Serving the chart as http://YOUR_SERVER_IP:5713 will NOT
# connect — use TLS (e.g. Caddy + Let's Encrypt) or SSH -L port forward to localhost.
#
# --- Vite dev server (Node only; not exposed to VITE_* bundle) ---
# Default listen: 0.0.0.0:5713 — same URL as http://localhost:5713 on the machine.
# CHART_WEB_PORT=5713
# When using Caddy in front of a real domain, allow the Host header and fix HMR (wss on 443):
# CHART_WEB_ALLOWED_HOSTS=dexfilter.xyz,www.dexfilter.xyz
# CHART_WEB_PUBLIC_ORIGIN=https://dexfilter.xyz
# — If you also keep the two lines above while opening the app at http://localhost:5713, set
#   CHART_WEB_USE_LOCAL_HMR=1 so the dev client uses WebSocket to localhost (not wss to the public
#   domain, which will fail). Remove or set to 0 when you browse via the real https URL.
# CHART_WEB_USE_LOCAL_HMR=1
# — Or comment out CHART_WEB_PUBLIC_ORIGIN for pure localhost dev.
#   “WebSocket closed without opened” on localhost: almost always the wrong HMR target — fix the two
#   lines above, or ensure Caddy proxies :443 → Vite with WebSocket upgrade.
# Fail startup if port is busy instead of trying another port:
# CHART_WEB_STRICT_PORT=1
# See repo file: deploy/caddy-dexfilter.xyz.Caddyfile
#
# --- VITE_RPC_URL (required for reliable browser use) ---
# Public https://api.mainnet-beta.solana.com is heavily rate-limited and often returns HTTP 403
# (or stalls) for browser-based JSON-RPC — migrate to a private HTTPS RPC.
#
# Alchemy Solana (example): free tier billed in Compute Units (~30M CU/month), high throughput
# (~25 req/s tier on published plans), HTTPS endpoint + dashboard. Create an app key, then set:
#   VITE_RPC_URL=https://solana-mainnet.g.alchemy.com/v2/<YOUR_API_KEY>
# Docs: https://www.alchemy.com/solana — pricing: https://www.alchemy.com/pricing
# Other providers (Helius, QuickNode, Triton, …) work the same way: paste your HTTPS RPC URL here.
#
# Fallback only if you accept breakage in the chart / Phantom panel:
# VITE_RPC_URL=https://api.mainnet-beta.solana.com
# VITE_TOKEN_MINT=EPjFWdd5AufqSSqeM2qN1xzybapC8G4wEGGkZwyTDt1v
# VITE_SOL_BOT_MAX_INPUT_RAW=5000000
# VITE_MODE — paper/replay = no on-chain broadcast from the panel; live = allow send when "Simulate only" is off.
# Automated signal swaps (chart desk) also require VITE_MODE=live.
# VITE_MODE=paper
# VITE_MODE=live
# VITE_SOL_BOT_KILL_SWITCH=0
#
# --- Automated signal execution (signing key + swap sizes) ---
# Base58 or JSON array — same as Phantom. WARNING: Vite inlines VITE_* into the browser bundle; use a
# dedicated hot wallet, never a master wallet, and do not commit .env. Restart dev server after change.
# VITE_DESK_PRIVATE_KEY=
# VITE_SIGNAL_BUY_LAMPORTS=1000000
# VITE_SIGNAL_SELL_TOKEN_RAW=10000
# VITE_SIGNAL_SLIPPAGE_BPS=100
# Optional client override for Jupiter base (e.g. static deploy on another origin, or a private relay).
# Do NOT set this to https://api.jup.ag/swap/v1 while running `npm run chart:dev` on localhost —
# the browser would call Jupiter directly and often hits ERR_TUNNEL_CONNECTION_FAILED (VPN/proxy).
# Leave unset for dev; chart uses same-origin `/jupiter-api` (Vite → https://api.jup.ag/swap/v1/…).
# VITE_JUPITER_API_BASE=https://your-cdn.example/swap-v1
#
# --- Vite dev server only (not VITE_*): Jupiter upstream for `/jupiter-api` proxy ---
# Default: https://api.jup.ag (paths rewritten to /swap/v1/quote, /swap/v1/swap, …)
# If you terminate Jupiter on your own host (nginx, etc.):
# JUPITER_API_PROXY_TARGET=https://your-internal-host
#
# Optional Pro key — forwarded as `x-api-key` on Node → Jupiter requests (never VITE_*):
# JUPITER_SWAP_API_KEY=your-api-key
#
# --- DNS for Jupiter / Gecko upstreams (Vite Node process only) ---
# Default: OS resolver (resolv.conf / systemd-resolved). Good for most machines.
# If the dev proxy logs ENOTFOUND for api.jup.ag, try CHART_WEB_USE_PUBLIC_DNS=1 or CHART_WEB_DNS_SERVERS (below), or fix system DNS.
#
# Broken VM / resolver returns bad AAAA: force Google+Cloudflare DNS in the Vite process:
# CHART_WEB_USE_PUBLIC_DNS=1
#
# Use only system resolver even when CHART_WEB_DNS_SERVERS / PUBLIC would apply (rare):
# CHART_WEB_USE_SYSTEM_DNS=1
#
# Custom DNS list (comma-separated); when set, used as-is (PUBLIC flag not required):
# CHART_WEB_DNS_SERVERS=8.8.8.8,1.1.1.1
#
# If you still see resolution failures, fix system DNS, e.g. Ubuntu:
#   sudo resolvectl dns "$(ip -4 route show default | awk '{print $5}' | head -1)" 8.8.8.8 1.1.1.1
#   sudo resolvectl flush-caches
# Test: getent hosts api.jup.ag
#
# --- When curl shows `CONNECT tunnel failed` or proxy breaks Node ---
# A broken HTTP(S)_PROXY is forcing CONNECT. From repo root use:
#   npm run chart:dev:direct-net
# or unset HTTPS_PROXY http_proxy HTTP_PROXY all_proxy for the shell that starts Vite.
#
# --- Browser shows 500 on `http://localhost:5173/jupiter-api/...` ---
# Vite returns 500 when the dev proxy cannot reach Jupiter (see the terminal running `chart:dev`:
# it logs `http proxy error:` with the real cause — ENOTFOUND, ETIMEDOUT, ECONNRESET, etc.).
# Fix DNS/network, or run `npm run chart:dev:direct-net` from the repo root if Node's proxy
# cannot reach Jupiter due to HTTPS_PROXY. Do not point VITE_JUPITER_API_BASE at api.jup.ag
# on localhost — use the default `/jupiter-api` proxy instead (see note above).
